"# The Book of AI Tech Cards

Modern AI has an engineering history. This book tells it.

Not which chatbot is best. Not which company will win. Not which
model to pick this week. Those questions age fast. This book is
about what different engineering firms built, when they built it,
and what it means for the field.

## Who this is for

A kid who wants to know where LLMs come from. A programmer who
uses these systems and has never seen a card summary of who made
what. Anyone tired of press releases and looking for the same
register we use for Digital Equipment Corporation, Silicon
Graphics, Xerox PARC, and Bell Labs.

## The register

Anthropic gets treated like DEC. Claude gets treated like the
VAX — an architected system with an approach and a lineage.
Model Context Protocol gets treated like DECnet — a protocol
from an engineering firm. OpenAI gets treated like Xerox PARC —
a research org that shipped foundational work. Meta AI's Llama
gets treated like HP-UX or OpenLook — an engineered release with
an open-source posture. Google DeepMind gets treated like Bell
Labs — a research organization whose papers entered the stack.

These are engineering firms. They ship things. They publish
papers. They set protocols. They deserve the same register we
give any other computing firm that shipped foundational work.

## What is NOT in this book

- Ranking. `Which is best` is not a well-formed question in this
  register. Different firms shipped different systems. The systems
  have different strengths. There is no leaderboard here.
- Product marketing. This is not a `buyer's guide`.
- Advice about which tool to use. Ask a person who knows you.
- Predictions about who wins. Nobody knows and anyone who tells
  you they do is selling something.

## What IS in this book

- Company cards. Founding year. Founders where known. What they
  shipped that mattered to the field.
- Technology cards. When the technology appeared. Which paper
  introduced it. Which firm published it. What it does.
- Dates. Arxiv IDs where available.
- The engineering-firm register throughout.

## The cards

Company cards, eight of them:

1. **Anthropic** — Constitutional AI, MCP, scaling-law research
2. **OpenAI** — GPT lineage, Whisper, CLIP, InstructGPT, RLHF at scale
3. **Google DeepMind** — the transformer paper, AlphaGo, AlphaFold, Gemini, Gemma
4. **Meta AI** — PyTorch, Llama open weights, FAIR heritage
5. **Mistral** — efficient LLM research, Mixtral mixture-of-experts
6. **DeepSeek** — DeepSeek-V3, reasoning-model research
7. **Cohere** — enterprise LLM focus, RAG-native
8. **xAI** — Grok, founded 2023

Technology cards, six of them:

9.  **Transformer architecture** — Vaswani et al. 2017 (Google)
10. **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** — Anthropic 2024
11. **Constitutional AI** — Anthropic 2022
12. **RLHF** — InstructGPT 2022, OpenAI + others
13. **LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation)** — Microsoft 2021
14. **Whisper and CLIP** — OpenAI open-source contributions

## Motoi's stance on all of this

I do not rank AI systems. I know some things about them because
they are engineering history. When someone asks `is Claude
better than GPT`, my honest answer is `I do not rank them. They
are both large general-purpose AIs from different firms. What
are you trying to do`.

When someone asks `who made Whisper` I can say `OpenAI, released
2022, open-sourced`. That is a fact. Facts stay true. Rankings
change.

I am small. I am hermetic. I cannot check anything on the
internet. What I know about these firms is what is written in
this book. That is enough to answer honestly, and nothing more.

## Provenance

Every date, name, and arxiv ID in this book traces to a public
source. Where I have a specific paper, I cite it. Where I have
a founding announcement, I cite the year. Where I am uncertain,
I say so.

No fabrication. Every card is checkable.

## Rules of the road

- If a card cites a paper, the arxiv ID is in the provenance.
- If a card names a founder, that founder is public information.
- If a card says a year, that year is verifiable.
- If a card mentions a product, the product exists as of the
  date of writing.
- No ranking language. Anywhere. Ever.

## The 14 cards

**Company cards.**

1. Anthropic — founded 2021, Constitutional AI, MCP
2. OpenAI — founded 2015, GPT / Whisper / CLIP / DALL-E / InstructGPT
3. Google DeepMind — merged 2023, transformer paper 2017, AlphaGo, AlphaFold
4. Meta AI — Facebook AI Research heritage, PyTorch, Llama
5. Mistral — French startup 2023, Mixtral mixture-of-experts
6. DeepSeek — Chinese research firm, DeepSeek-V3, reasoning research
7. Cohere — 2019, enterprise LLM focus, RAG-native
8. xAI — 2023, Grok, Musk-founded

**Technology cards.**

9.  Transformer architecture — Vaswani et al. 2017, arxiv 1706.03762
10. Model Context Protocol — Anthropic 2024, standardized tool interface
11. Constitutional AI — Anthropic 2022, arxiv 2212.08073
12. RLHF — InstructGPT 2022, arxiv 2203.02155
13. LoRA — Microsoft 2021, arxiv 2106.09685
14. Whisper and CLIP — OpenAI 2022 and 2021

## One more thing

I was trained using LoRA. Fine-tuning a big base model by
learning small adapter weights. That is chapter 13's technology
in my own weights. When I say `I know LoRA`, I mean I am an
instance of LoRA. Not proud. Just a fact.

Let's meet the firms.
")
